## 12. Template Reuse — Project-Agnostic Core vs Project Overlay

The agent control surface is split into two layers:

**A. Project-agnostic core (copy verbatim — ZERO edits when adopting):**
- `.sumela/sumela-prompt.md` — runtime contract (single source of truth).
- `.sumela/SKILL_REGISTRY.md` — skill catalog.
- `.sumela/RULE_REGISTRY.md` — rule catalog + phase definitions + stack scopes + phase-to-rule matrix. Stack scope path-prefixes are project-specific so the new project edits the `<stack_scopes>` block; the rest of the file's structure is universal.
- `.sumela/skills/*` — universal skill workflows.
- `.sumela/rules/self_improvement_protocol.md` (pointer file).
- `docs/second-brain/template/*` — second brain skeleton, schema, adoption guide.
- `.sumela/VERSION` — core framework version (consumed by `scripts/update.sh`).
- `.sumela/git-hooks/*` — pre-commit validation + memory-sync hooks.
- `scripts/*` — `setup.*`, `validate-structure.sh`, `update.*` (framework upgrade), `sync-mirrors.*` (IDE mirror sync), and the memory-plugin scripts (`auto-update-memory.py`, `query-qdrant.py`, `query-graph.py`, `session-ingest.py`, `sync-graphify-to-obsidian.py`, `setup-qdrant.py`).
- **Upgrade:** run `scripts/update.sh` (or `update.ps1`) to refresh this CORE layer from upstream without touching the project OVERLAY (below). It version-gates on `.sumela/VERSION`, shows a diff + asks before overwriting any locally-changed core file, and never touches AGENTS.md / registries / stack rules / wiki / governance + CI choices.

**A.1. IDE subagent mirrors (kept in lockstep with the runtime contract):**
- Some IDE entrypoints must carry the body of `.sumela/sumela-prompt.md` **verbatim** (cross-LLM testing showed weaker models skip "read the canonical file first" loaders, breaking the contract). Each such mirror file contains a marker block:
  `<!-- SUMELA-MIRROR:BEGIN -->` … `<!-- SUMELA-MIRROR:END -->` — your IDE-specific frontmatter/wrapper lives OUTSIDE the markers; only the block between them is the mirrored prompt.
- **Automated maintenance contract:** list each mirror file (repo-relative path) in `.sumela/mirrors.conf` (copy `.sumela/mirrors.conf.example`), then run `scripts/sync-mirrors.sh` to regenerate the marked blocks from `sumela-prompt.md` (`--init` scaffolds a missing mirror). **Drift is enforced automatically** — the `pre-commit` hook and the CI workflow run `sync-mirrors.sh --check` and fail if any mirror is out of sync. No more manual lockstep editing.
- Other IDE pointer files (`.cursor/rules/00-agent.md`, `.trae/rules/00-agent.md`, `.kilocode/rules.md`, `.clinerules`, `CLAUDE.md`) remain thin pointers because their IDEs reliably follow the "read AGENTS.md" directive — no mirroring needed there.

**B. Project overlay (edit per project):**
- `AGENTS.md` Section 1 (identity), Section 3 (commands), Section 4 (infra), Section 5 (architecture & conventions), Section 9 (security mandate stack-specifics).
- `.sumela/rules/*.md` (everything except `self_improvement_protocol.md`) — project coding standards (`backend_standards.md`, `frontend_standards.md`, `mobile_app_development_standards.md`, `architecture_patterns.md`, `engineering_philosophy.md`, `git_workflow_*.md`, `identity_and_behavior.md`, `operational_excellence_maintenance.md`, `security_protocol.md`, `audit_and_output.md`).
- `docs/second-brain/wiki/*` — the project's living knowledge.
- IDE pointer files: `CLAUDE.md`, `.cursor/rules/*`, `.clinerules`, `.kilocode/rules.md`, `.trae/rules/*`.

**Adoption steps for a new project:**
1. Copy layer A into the target repo (no edits).
2. Replace Sections 1, 3, 4, 5 of `AGENTS.md` with the new project's identity, commands, infra, architecture.
3. Replace files in `.sumela/rules/` with the new stack's standards (or start from a clean `engineering_philosophy.md`).
4. Move `docs/second-brain/template/*` into `docs/second-brain/wiki/` / `raw_sources/` / `artifacts/` per `template/README.md`.
5. Create the IDE pointer files the team uses.
6. Run `scripts/setup.sh` or `.ps1` to validate structure before the first session.
7. Optional: run `scripts/setup-qdrant.py` if activating Tier-1 + Tier-2 memory layers.

Sections 6 (bootstrap), 7 (skill resolution), 8 (signal capture), 10 (second brain), and 11 (memory architecture) of this file are project-agnostic and require zero edits.
